<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-235-152 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 344 854</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Jan 31 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Japanese MS-DOS 5.0 debuts in April. (Microsoft Corp.'s operatingsystem)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Miyazawa, Masayuki.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Product development).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   MS-DOS 5.0 (Operating system) (Product development).andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentOperating SystemsJapanese Language.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>JAPANESE MS-DOS 5.0 DEBUTS IN APRIL 01/31/91 TOKYO, JAPAN, 1991 JAN 31 (NB)-- A Japanese language version of MS-DOS version 5.0 is expected to bereleased in April, according to a Newsbytes source.andP;  That will be only amonth's delay from the release of the new MS-DOS 5.0 in the U.S.andM;The Japanese subsidiary of Microsoft is currently adding Japanese languagefeatures to the original MS-DOS 5.0.andP;  The project is said to be on schedule.andO;The latest version of the de facto standard operating system occupies only 15kilobytes of main memory while current versions use 100 kilobytes.andP;  As aresult, the user should be able to exploit a larger memory area for whichsoftware makers can develop more powerful application programs.andM;Currently, IBM Japan and Seiko-Epson have been using MS-DOS 4.0 and NEC isusing 3.3.andP;  Recently, NEC has released a Japanese version of MS-Windows 3.0and IBM is going on for DOS/V and OS/2.andP;  From this point of view, there areample candidates offering what they hope will be a future standard operatingsystem.andP;  So, it may be too early to forecast the success of Japanese MS-DOS5.0.andM;Microsoft says application developers need to make fundamental modificationsto existing applications in order to make them run on MS-DOS 5.0.andP;  Because ofthis, the future of MS-DOS 5.0 is particularly uncertain.andM;(Masayuki Miyazawa/19910131/Press Contact: Microsoft, Tokyo office, andplus;81-3-3363-1200)</TEXT></DOC>